  <thing id="rBhuka" name="Bhuka" description="The bhukas are a goblinoid people who claim descent from the first inhabitants of the world. Their culture celebrates and preserves ancestral ways of living.\n\n{b}Personality{/b}: Although not technologically advanced, bhukas are a sophisticated people with developed art and social organization. They are not warlike, so they avoid conflict via stealth. A bhuka never approaches strangers but observes from hiding as long as possible to gauge thier intent.\n\n{b}Physical Description{/b}: Bhukas are slight (4-5 ft tall and rarely more than 90 lb), with sand-colored skin and brick-red, tightly curled hair. Their large ears, networked with veins, fold flat against the head to retain heat at night and keep out sand. A neck frill has spines that can lift it for cooling. The face of a bhuka is flat, with slit nostrils protected by skinflaps. Bhuka&#146;s have long lashes to keep out dust, and the skin around the eyes is dark, resembling a mask. Their wide feet aid movement over sand. Body paint signifies social position (a simple stripe on a youth&#146;s neck frill to elaborate spotted, striped or whorled patterns on a matriarch). Clothing is woven from desert grasses that protect from heat.\n\n{b}Relations{/b}: From the beginning of their history, bhukas have been a gentle people exploited by others. When the first people emerged from the Lower World, bhukas were the last to choose a home and had to adapt to the waste. Cruder goblinoids call them weak, while badland dwarves and painted elves are often friendly. Warlike races drove bhukas away from fertile lands, yet they take pride in flourishing in the waste. They aren&apos;t cowards&#151;push too hard, and they reveal a toughness bred of harsh living. They have trade relations with crucians but the asheratis&#146; presence below the sand challenges a bhuka&#146;s perception of reality and standing in the waste heirarchy.\n\n{b}Alignment{/b}: A complex system of relationships hold bhuka villages together. Respect for superiors and contribution to the common good is drilled into all members of society, and those who will not become outcasts. Bhuka society is lawful, with most tending toward good.\n\n{b}Bhuka Lands{/b}: Bhukas form extended groups of several related clans, called phratries. Each claims ancestry from one couple who emerged from the Lower World in the beginning and must maintain a particular tradition of the people. Bhukas inhabit adobe or sandstone dwellings built into and against cliffs or dug into the upper levels of desert canyons. The entrance to a house is well above ground level for defense&#151;access is by ladders or rope lifts. A central spring provides water to the community.\n\nFarms use traditional dry-farming techniques to grow their staple foods of beans, sunflowers, desert grasses, and corn. \n\n{b}Religion{/b}: Each phratry is responsible for protecting a relic of the Emergence, the time when the first people came out from under the earth. For example, members of the Wokuhoo (Moon Owl) phratry are the caretakers of the Talon, a relic of the bird that led their ancestors into the Upper World. \n\nVillages are headed by a Grandmother who presides over a council of male and female elders. The Lower World from which they came is called Second Womb, where Kikanuti nurtured and taught them until they were ready to emerge. Their savage cousins are immature and must stay underground. Grandmother is the link to Kikanuti and presides over ceremonies where clan elders don ritual masks to dance.\n\n{b}Language{/b}: All Bhuka lore is oral, supplemented by a rich library of symbols that adorn both artistic and everyday objects. Their tongue is related to Goblin, but has diverged enough to be incomprehensible to other goblins.\n\n{b}Names{/b}: Bhuka names carry meaning, but retain harsh Goblin syllables. Most have a given name, mother&#146;s clan (prefix {i}kha{/i}, &#147;born of&#148;), and marriage clan (prefix {i}gi{/i}). Children have pet names until they choose an adult name.\n\n{b}Male Given Names{/b}: Aghila&#146;ak (Runs Like Lizard), Cochik&#146;ukan (Eyes of Sunhawk), Kotigana (Ears of Hare), Niskigan (Snake Fang).\n\n{b}Female Given Names{/b}: Chinkichu (Basket of Corn), Hintak&#146;inai (Painted Frill), Kekkoti (Little Ear), Lakinigo (Slow Smile).\n\n{b}Clan Names{/b}: Clans are named for a totem spirit or relic. Chikuk (Sunhawk), Kekkinna (Ear of Corn), Kichu (Basket), Wiki&#146;i (Swallow).\n\n{b}Adventurers{/b}: Bhuka&apos;s tight-knit community seldom produces wanderers, but ancient migrations remain part of racial memory. Some born with wind in their souls carry messages and gifts to scattered villages or lead trade expeditions to crucian lands. Those in whom the wind blows strongest go to see where the other children of Kikanuti went, or just follow their hearts. \n\nOutcast bhukas (usually bitter, selfish beings) also rove the waste. Some yearn to belong and may find a sense of community among other races." compset="Race">
